data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    foreach (var user in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} is not active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(all match)` | Loop + assert with message | Identifies *which* item failed |

Also useful from `CollectionAssert`: `Contains`, `AreEquivalent`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, and `IsSubsetOf`.
